{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionIt is critical for policy and clinical guidelines to be based on the best available evidence [5].",
    "Systematic reviews are often regarded as the gold standard for evidence synthesis [8], appraising the latest evidence transparently and objectively by employing established standards [2].",
    "Consequently, poorly conducted systematic reviews can potentially misinform future clinical guidelines and policies [8].",
    "Misinformed clinical guidelines could equip practitioners with inaccurate scientific information and clinical advice, compromising the quality of care [9].",
    "Additionally, misinformed clinical guidelines could potentially encourage ineffective, harmful, or wasteful interventions [9].In recent years, as the number of primary studies continues to increase, current methods of manual information extraction by researchers for the synthesis of systematic reviews is not sustainable and efficient."
  ],
